Our virtual text display buffer is nothing more than a region of raw memory set aside in the .bss section, using the 'RESB' directive. 
The size of the buffer is defined by two equates, which specify the number of rows and columns that you want. 
By default its set to 25 rows and 80 columns. 
You can change the 'COLS' and 'ROWS' equates to define buffers as large as 255 X 255, though if your terminal window isn't that large, your results will be unpredictable. 
Changing the dimensions of your text display is done by changing one or both of these equates. 
Whatever other changes must be made to the code are handled automatically. 
Note that this has to be done at assembly time, as many of the calculations are assembly-time calculations done by NASM when you build the program. 

You do not have to match the size of the terminal window precisely to the 'ROWS x COLS'. 
If yu maximize the terminal window your text display will appear starting in the upper-left corner of the screen.

